choices.text:
a betrayal of the family’s honor

In Azerbaijan, social and religious forces working behind the scenes to strengthen conservative and patriarchal gender norms are combing various media channels with cultural expression. They argue that female hypergamy is establishing Azerbaijan's Muslim heritage as a new world order is emerging. They claim that if women continue to reject conservative principles and norms, "uncontrollable" women risk rising prices, corruption, sexual assault, loss of family and community honor, and controlled migration.

There are a wide range of stories about how to tell profound love stories in Azerbaijan’s more isolated regions in line with these emerging gender norms, according to the researchers. One series of stories offers this account of love and marriage in the countryside:

“Marriage [to men] allows women to participate in a range of economic activities in which they can have their material needs satisfied … be beautiful and rich … And women would prefer to be understood as a husband and wife in all that they Do in life. Whenever [men] are sick, you will share your illness At first glance and you will comfort each other, when you get rich together [in the future], you will share your satisfaction together. Every man aspires for such love in his youth, but nowadays women are inclined to refuse this love.”
